==Production==
''Rob-B-Hood'' is a joint production of Huayi Brothers Film Investment Company and Jackie Chan Emperor Movies Limited, a company set up by Jackie Chan following [[Golden Harvest]]'s departure from the film industry.<ref name = "Variety">{{cite web
  | last = Jay
  | first = Weissberg
  | title = Rob-B-Hood Review
  | work =
  | publisher = Variety
  | date = 2006-09-14
  | url = http://www.variety.com/review/VE1117931584.html?categoryid=31&cs=1
  | accessdate = 2007-07-27 }}</ref> Having starred in over [[Jackie Chan filmography|40 action comedy films]] over the course of his acting career, Chan was tired of being typecast as an actor who plays "Mr. Nice Guy" in his films.<ref>{{cite news
  | title = Jackie Chan: From action maestro to serious actor
  | work = China Daily
  | date = [[2004-09-24]]
  | url = http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/english/doc/2004-09/24/content_377571.htm
  | accessdate = 2007-06-09 }}</ref> Following ''[[New Police Story]]'' and ''[[The Myth]]'', ''Rob-B-Hood'' is the third film in which Chan attempted to introduce more dramatic elements in his films.<ref name="Bad Person">{{cite news 
  | title = Jackie Chan states he can't play the role of a bad person (成龙：我不能演大坏人)
  | language = Simplified Chinese
  | publisher = The Beijing News
  | date = 2006-04-12
  | url = http://ent.thebeijingnews.com/0606/2006/04-12/013@014338.htm
  | accessdate = 2007-08-15 }}</ref>

''Rob-B-Hood'' is the first film in which Jackie Chan plays an [[anti-hero]]. In an attempt to shed the image of "Mr. Nice Guy", Chan plays the role of Thongs, a burglar fallen out with his family over his [[problem gambling|gambling habit]].<ref>{{cite web
  | title = For the first time, Chan plays an unconventional role in his newest comedy (成龙首次尝试反派 联手陈木胜再拍动作喜剧)
  | work = Sina
  | date = [[2005-12-30]]
  | url = http://ent.sina.com.cn/m/c/2005-12-30/0832945759.html
  | language = Simplified Chinese
  | accessdate = 2007-06-09 }}</ref> Despite Thongs' imprisonment at the end of the film, Chan described his character as no more than a petty crook, citing Thong's [[repentance]] as the key element of the plot.<ref name="Bad Person"/>

The plot was partly inspired by the American film ''[[Home Alone]]'', but focused on a gang of burglars rather than a boy left alone to protect his home from burglars.<ref>{{cite web 
  | title = Jackie Chan and Gao Yuanyuan share thier thoughts after filming (《宝贝计划》关机 成龙高圆圆畅谈感受)
  | work = Sina
  | language = Simplified Chinese
  | date = 2006-04-11
  | url = http://ent.sina.com.cn/m/2006-04-11/17211046243.html
  | accessdate = 2007-08-17 }}
</ref> It was jointly written by Jackie Chan and Benny Chan, the director. Jackie Chan designed the fighting scenes while Benny Chan focused on its dramatic elements,<ref name="BC In">{{cite web
  | title = Interview with Director Benny Chan (專訪《寶貝計劃》主創 導演陳木勝談新片)
  | work = Sina
  | publisher = China Movie Database
  | date = [[2006-09-09]]
  | url = http://hk.cnmdb.com/newsent/20060909/800187
  | language = Traditional Chinese
  | accessdate = 2007-07-27 }}</ref> completing the script by October 2005.<ref name="Story">{{cite web
  | title = Jackie Chan has written the plot of the new film, and plans to co-star with Sammo Hung and Yuen Biao (成龙：自己完成新片剧本 将与洪金宝元彪再聚首)
  | work = Huaxiangbao
  | publisher = Sina
  | date = [[2005-10-11]]
  | url = http://ent.sina.com.cn/m/c/2005-10-11/0725861740.html
  | language = Simplified Chinese
  | accessdate = 2007-06-09 }}</ref> The film's Chinese title was chosen to be ''Bo Bui Gai Wak'' ([[Cantonese (linguistics)|Cantonese]]: 寶貝計劃) as a reference to ''[[Project A]]'' (Cantonese: ''A Gai Wak'', A計劃), one of Jackie Chan's early films.<ref name="LHKF">{{cite web
  | title = Rob-B-Hood Film Review
  | publisher = LoveHKFilm
  | url = http://www.lovehkfilm.com/reviews_2/rob_b_hood.htm
  | accessdate = 2007-08-07 }}</ref>

=== Casting ===
[[Image:Rbh C.JPG|thumb|left|Yuen Biao, one of the Three Brothers, appears alongside Jackie Chan for the first time in many years in the film ''Rob-B-Hood''.]]
The cast of ''Rob-B-Hood'' included a crew of actors ranging from debutante [[Gao Yuanyuan]] to veteran actor Chen Baoguo.<ref>{{cite web
|last = Kang
|first = Xiaoning
|title = Chen Baoguo returns to the big screen in Rob-B-Hood(陈宝国重新回归大银幕 《BB计划》演黑帮头目)
|work = Shenyang Daily
|publisher = Sina
|language = Simplified Chinese
|url = http://ent.sina.com.cn/m/c/2006-03-29/11441031183.html
|date = 2006-03-29
|accessdate = 2007-08-30}}</ref> [[Daniel Wu]] and [[Nicholas Tse]], stars of ''[[New Police Story]]'' made cameo apperances as [[homosexual]] [[Armored car#Valuables transport|security van]] drivers during a car chase in the film.<ref>{{citeweb
|last = Sutherland
|first = Stewart
|title = Rob-B-Hood review
|publisher = Hong Kong Cinema UK
|url = http://www.hkcuk.co.uk/reviews/rob_b_hood.htm
|date = 2006
|accessdate = 2007-08-30}}</ref>

Octopus, Thong's partner in crime, is played by Louis Koo, an award winning actor with experience ranging from [[Television Broadcasts Limited|TVB]] drama series ''[[Detective Investigation Files IV]]'' and the film ''[[Election 2]]''. Koo is proud to work with Jackie Chan, describing him as an upright [[perfectionist]] who forbids [[littering]] by crew members in the premises, volunteering to take out the rubbish. Despite sharing the same amount of screen time with Jackie Chan, Koo admitted he was spellbound by Chan's stunts, feeling slightly inconfident acting alongside him.<ref>{{cite web
  | title = Louis Koo is particularly fond of Jackie Chan (古天乐向影帝偷师学做人 尤其敬佩成龙)
  | work = 金羊网-羊城晚报
  | date = [[2005-12-08]]
  | url = http://www.ycwb.com/gb/content/2005-12/08/content_1034410.htm
  | language = Simplified Chinese
  | accessdate = 2007-08-17 }}</ref> Koo was the baby's favourite on set, and whenever the baby cried, Koo was always the first to cheer him up. <ref name = "Hui">{{cite web
  | title = Michael Hui will not fight in Rob-B-Hood, Louis Koo is popular (许冠文《宝贝计划》不动手 古天乐受欢迎)
  | work = Sina
  | date = [[2006-04-11]]
  | url = http://ent.sina.com.cn/m/2006-04-11/17451046258.html
  | language = Simplified Chinese
  | accessdate = 2007-08-19 }}</ref> 

The Landlord, the leader behind Thongs and Octopus, is played by Michael Hui, a comedian who has starred in various films in the 1980s and 1990s before emigrating to [[Canada]] shortly before the [[Transfer of the sovereignty of Hong Kong|handover of Hong Kong]]. Jackie Chan chose Hui because he is the ideal actor to play someone who would tempt others to do bad things.<ref name="The Nation">{{cite web
  | last = Pajee
  | first = Parinyaporn
  | title = Jackie's bundle of joy
  | work = The Nation
   | date = [[2006-09-28]]
  | url = http://www.nationmultimedia.com/2006/09/28/entertainment/entertainment_30014853.php
  | accessdate = 2007-08-17 }}</ref> The producers had originally intended Hui to fight along with Jackie Chan and Louis Koo, eventually it was decided that Hui will simply act as the brains behind the duo.<ref name = "Hui"/>

''Rob-B-Hood'' features the collaboration between Jackie Chan and [[Yuen Biao]], a fellow member of the [[Seven Little Fortunes]]. Yuen Biao, a close friend of Chan, has co-starred with Chan and [[Sammo Hung]] in a number of action comedy films in the 1980s including ''Project A'', ''[[Wheels on Meals]]'' and the ''[[Lucky Stars]]'' trilogy. Chan had originally intended to co-star with both Yuen Biao and Sammo Hung as a reunion of the "Three Brothers". However, the latter declined. Only Yuen Biao appears in the film, playing the role of Police Inspector Mok, a policeman assigned to investigate the baby's disappearance.<ref>{{cite web
  | title = Jackie Chan plans to collaborate with Sammo Hung and Yuen Biao (成龙：自己完成新片剧本 将与洪金宝元彪再聚首)
  | work = 金羊网-羊城晚报
  | date = [[2005-10-11]]
  | url = http://fun.huash.com/gb/fun/2005-10/11/content_2278127.htm
  | language = Simplified Chinese
  | accessdate = 2007-08-17 }}</ref><ref name="LHKF"/>

It took over 100 auditions to find the suitable baby to star in ''Rob-B-Hood''.<ref name="BC"/> Benny Chan chose Matthew Medvedev, a one year old infant of Chinese and Columbian descent. Medvedev, known as Baby Matthew, was literally recruited off the street when an assistant director spotted him with his parents on the [[MTR]]. Although his family was simply visiting Hong Kong, they agreed to stay and let Matthew appear in ''Rob-B-Hood''.<ref name="The Nation"/>

=== Filming ===
[[Image:Rbh E.JPG|thumb|right|Jackie Chan, Yuen Biao, Benny Chan and Louis Koo take a break during filming in Central.]]
''Rob-B-Hood'' is the third Jackie Chan film directed by Benny Chan, following ''[[Who Am I?]]'' and ''New Police Story''.<ref name = BC/> Filming took place in Hong Kong between December 2005 and April 2006 with a budget of [[Hong Kong dollar|HK$]]16.8 million.<ref>{{cite web
  | title = Production of Project BB has begun (《宝贝计划》开镜 成龙古天乐高圆圆出席)
  | work = Xinhuanet
  | publisher = Sina
  | date = [[2005-12-30]]
  | url = http://ent.sina.com.cn/m/c/2005-12-30/0850945383.html
  | language = Simplified Chinese
  | accessdate = 2007-07-27 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web
  | title = Jackie Chan celebrates the completion of filming in Beijing (北京关机 成龙：我不能演大坏人)
  | work = New Beijing Daily
  | publisher = Sina
  | date = [[2006-04-12]]
  | url = http://ent.sina.com.cn/m/c/2006-04-12/01431046459.html
  | language = Simplified Chinese
  | accessdate = 2007-08-07 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web
  | title = Rob-B-Hood Movie Information
  | publisher = Allocine
  | url = http://www.allocine.fr/film/fichefilm_gen_cfilm=115025.html
  | language = French
  | accessdate = 2007-07-27 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web
  | title = Picture of Jackie Chan during the night shooting at Ocean Park
  | publisher = Official Jackie Chan Website
  | date = [[2006-01-29]]
  | url = http://www.jackiechan.com/photos_view?cid=625
  | accessdate = 2007-08-07 }}</ref> Filming locations include [[Central, Hong Kong|Central]], [[Sai Kung]], [[Sha Tin]], [[Ocean Park Hong Kong|Hong Kong Ocean Park]] and even a decomissioned prison.<ref>{{cite web
| title = The Final Scene of ROB-B-HOOD (aka. PROJECT BB) at a Hong Kong Prison
| date = 2006-04-27
| publisher = MonkeyPeaches
| url = http://www.monkeypeaches.com/0604M.html
| accessdate = 2007-08-31}}</ref><ref>{{cite web
| title = Picture of Jackie Chan while filming Rob-B-Hood in Ocean Park
| date = 2007-01-29
| publisher = Official website of Jackie Chan
| url = http://www.jackiechan.com/photos_view?cid=625
| accessdate = 2007-08-31}}</ref>

Benny Chan described the filming process as one of the darkest days of his career, citing the baby to be a factor beyond his control. The baby never did what he was told and could not work more than eight hours a day. Whenever a scene involving the baby was shot, the crew members could not make any noise and had to communicate in [[sign language]]. Benny Chan states it takes time, patience and money to guide the baby through each shot, and numerous retakes were required due to the baby's constant crying and napping. As a result, production went [[Cost overrun|over budget]].<ref name="BC"/> Crude methods were sometimes used to coax the baby into cooperation. One scene required the baby to bite Jackie Chan's [[nipple]]. The baby was initially hesitant, but relented after the crew brushed a large amount of [[honey]] onto the nipple.<ref>{{cite video
  | people = Jackie Chan
  | title = Rob-B-Hood Outtakes
  | medium = DVD/Cinema
  | publisher = JCE Pictures
  | location = Hong Kong
  | date = 2006 }}</ref>

The script was modified slightly during filming. One scene required Louis Koo to hug Jackie Chan from behind once they have found the baby, having left him on a bus. In one of the takes, Koo fell onto Chan as he ran for the baby, delivering a brief [[french kiss]] to Jackie Chan. The scene was immediately cut by director Benny Chan. Since the director loved the take, the script was changed on the spot to accommodate it.<ref>{{cite web
  | title = Two actors changed the script by kissing each other on the street (两猛男改剧本演激情 成龙与古天乐当街拥吻)
  | work = China News
  | date = [[2006-01-16]]
  | url = http://www.chinanews.com.cn/news/2006/2006-01-16/8/678994.shtml
  | language = Simplified Chinese
  | accessdate = 2007-08-11 }}</ref>

Jackie Chan turned 52 on [[April 7]], 2006, a few days before the end of filming. With a tight schedule to keep, Jackie Chan opted to spend his birthday working. However, his crew had planned a [[surprise birthday party]] for several days. During his dinner break, all production staff, including board members of the production company, arrived taking pictures with Jackie Chan, while actor [[Terence Yin]] presented him with two birthday cakes and a roast [[suckling pig]]. Several [[England|English]], [[Australia]]n and [[Japan]]ese fans attended Jackie Chan's birthday party, making the total number of guests exceed 100.<ref>{{cite web
  | title = Over 100 guests sang Jackie Chan's birthday song on set (成龙52岁生日片场度过 百人唱生日歌庆贺)
  | work = Sina
  | date = [[2006-04-09]]
  | url = http://ent.sina.com.cn/s/h/p/2006-04-09/10561043703.html
  | language = Simplified Chinese
  | accessdate = 2007-08-31 }}</ref>

=== Stunt work ===
[[Image:Rbh F.JPG|thumb|Jackie Chan hangs on the tracks of a roller coaster with the baby in hand.]]
Despite being over 50, Jackie Chan continued his tradition of performing his own stunts in ''Rob-B-Hood'', choreographed by the [[Jackie Chan Stunt Team]].<ref name = BJN/> Several scenes in the film required Jackie Chan to coordinate his stunts with the baby. They include a car chase around the Sha Tin industrial area, in which Jackie Chan managed to snatch the baby away seconds before a car crashes into him, and a scene in Ocean Park in which Chan climbed on the underside of a [[roller coaster]] with the baby on his back.<ref name="BC"/><ref name="Film">{{cite video
  | people = Jackie Chan
  | title = Rob-B-Hood
  | medium = DVD
  | publisher = JCE Pictures
  | location = Hong Kong
  | date = 2006 }}</ref> Jackie Chan suffered several minor injuries attempting stunts in the film. He was kicked in the chest by a stuntman wearing the wrong boots and fell off a [[quad bike]] attempting to perform a [[wheelie]].<ref>{{cite web
  | title = Stunt mishap sends Jackie to Hospital
  | work = Official website of Jackie Chan
  | date = [[2006-03-23]]
  | url = http://www.jackiechan.com/news_view?cid=183
  | accessdate = 2007-08-12 }}</ref> Like many of his previous films, Chan made use of [[improvised weapon]]s in combat. When he fought a pair of skilled henchmen in a deep frozen room, he defeated them by blowing cold air at them through a large [[fan]].<ref name=Film/>

==Cast==
[[Image:Rbh B.JPG|right|thumb|Matthew Medvedev plays the baby in ''Rob-B-Hood''.]]
*'''[[Jackie Chan]]''' (成龍) as '''Thongs''' (人字拖), a professional burglar who has stolen a variety of expensive goods. A compulsive gambler, Thongs has fallen out with his family over his lifestyle, resulting in his father having a [[stroke]].
*'''[[Louis Koo]]''' (古天樂) as '''[[Octopus card|Octopus]]''' (八達通), a fellow burglar working with Thongs. Octopus uses the money he stole to buy expensive cars and court a rich girl. He neglects his pregnant wife (played by [[Charlene Choi]]), forcing her into a series of dead end jobs to make ends meet.
*'''[[Michael Hui]]''' (許冠文) as the '''Landlord''' (包租公), mentor of Thongs and Octopus for over 20 years. Unlike his trainees, the Landlord does not spend his share of the loot, stashing it in a [[safe]] at home instead.
*'''Matthew Medvedev''' (or simply Baby Matthew) as the '''baby''' son of the wealthy Lee family kidnapped by Thongs, Octopus and the Landlord on behalf of a [[triad]] boss.
*'''[[Yuen Biao]]''' (元彪) as '''Inspector Mok''' (莫史迪), a policeman in charge of the case involving the baby's disappearance.
*'''[[Teresa Carpio]]''' as the '''Landlady''' (包租婆), wife of the Landlord. Driven mad by the death of her only son many years ago, the Landlady carries a doll of a baby boy with her at all times.
*'''[[Gao Yuanyuan]]''' (高圓圓) as '''Melody''', a student nurse from the [[Peking University]]. She works as a part time childcare consultant, teaching Thongs and Octopus how to take care of the baby.
*'''[[Terence Yin]]''' as '''Max''', former boyfriend of the baby's mother who claims the baby as his. He dies of a fall following a struggle for the baby in a hospital soon after his birth.
*'''Chen Baoguo''' (陳寶國) as the '''triad boss''', who thinks the baby is his grandson. Having lost his only son Max, the boss will stop at nothing to capture the baby.

==Plot==
[[Image:Rbh A.JPG|thumb|Octopus, Thongs and the Landlord prepare to kidnap the baby from the mansion.]]
The film begins showing two simultaneous events in a hospital: A burglary committed by Thongs and Octopus, and the birth of a baby boy to the wealthy [[Li (surname)|Lee]] family. Max, the mother's ex-boyfriend snatches the baby, prompting the security guards to pursue Max, ignoring the burglars. After a violent struggle on an escalator, Max and the baby fall over the side, the latter saved by Thongs. While the guards are distracted, Thongs and Octopus leave in the Landlord's [[minivan]].

A few months later, the Landlord lost his life savings following a burglary of his flat. Desperate to regain his fortunes, he accepts a job to kidnap baby Lee on behalf of [[triad society|triads]]. En route to their rendezvous point at [[Sai Kung]], the Landlord crashes their vehicle down a slope in an attempt to evade a police [[road block]]. Per the stuck Landlord's instructions, Thongs and Octopus leave with the baby, bringing him to the Landlord's flat before the police catch up.
 
The Landlord is detained by the police for [[reckless driving]]. Having learnt of the baby's potential value through the news, he phones Thongs, instructing him not to hand the baby over to anyone prior to his release. Over the next few days, Thongs and Octopus take care of the baby, developing a strong bond with him. The two begin to regret their vices: Thongs resists the urge to gamble, while Octopus feels sorry for cheating on his wife.

Meanwhile, both the triads and the police are after the baby. The triad boss, enraged by the non-delivery of his "grandson", sends his men to retrieve the baby from Thongs' flat. Having confronted both the triads and the police, led by Inspector Mok, Thongs and Octopus flee with the baby. Having failed to snatch the baby, the triads grab the Landlord as he is released from police custody and brings him to the triad boss, who now offers [[Hong Kong dollar|HK$]]30 million for the Baby. 

The Landlord finds Thongs and Octopus at the hospital, where the baby is being treated for fever. The Landlord shows them the HK$5 million deposit received from the triads, but Thongs and Octopus are more concerned about the baby. The two, however, agree to bring the baby to the triad boss' mansion, where the Landlord will meet them with the rest of the money. All seems fine, until the three see the nurses taking a blood sample from the baby. Thongs and Octopus experience a flashback of the days they spent with the baby, and are overcome by their feelings with him. They fight their way into the triad boss' private amusement park to recover the baby while the Landlord leaves with the money. Thongs almost manages to escape with the baby, but is forced to surrender when the triads threaten to hurl Octopus to his death.

[[Image:Rbh D.JPG|thumb|Thongs, Octopus and the baby hug each other for warmth in the frozen room.]]
Thongs and Octopus are taken to the triad boss, who insists the baby is his. However, he is proven wrong by the [[blood test]]. Driven mad, the boss places the baby in the frozen room next to Max's corpse. Thongs and Octopus decide to fight for the baby, ending up trapped in the frozen room with two minions. Fortunately, they are saved when Inspector Mok arrives with the Landlord, who swiftly cracks the lock to the room.

Thongs desperately attempts to revive the [[coma|comatose]] baby with a makeshift [[defibrillator]] powered by a [[car battery]]. The baby does not come to and is driven off in an [[ambulance]], where his heart is found to be beating weakly. Imprisoned for kidnapping, Thongs, Octopus and the Landlord volunteer for a mock [[capital punishment]] demonstration during an open day, using the opportunity to apologise to their loved ones. Inspector Mok informs the three that their sentences have been further reduced. The Lee family arrives, thanking them for saving the baby's life. As a token of appreciation, Thongs, Octopus and the Landlord are offered jobs in their household as a bodyguard, driver and head of security respectively.

